  "attributes": {
    "input.value": "{\"messages\": [[{\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"HumanMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"Explain Dark Matter\", \"type\": \"human\"}}]]}",
    "input.mime_type": "application/json",
    "output.value": "{\"generations\": [[{\"text\": \"Dark matter is a type of matter that does not emit, absorb, or reflect light, so we can\u2019t see it directly with telescopes. But we can see its gravity. Astrophysicists invoke dark matter to explain why galaxies rotate as they do, how galaxies cluster, and many features of the universe's large-scale structure.\\n\\nWhat we know (evidence in brief)\\n- Galaxy rotation curves: stars far from a galaxy\u2019s center orbit faster than visible matter alone would predict, implying extra unseen mass.\\n- Galaxy clusters: galaxies move as if they\u2019re wrapped in much more mass than the visible galaxies and hot gas indicate.\\n- Gravitational lensing: light from distant objects is bent by gravity in ways that reveal more mass than is visible.\\n- Cosmic microwave background (CMB) and structure formation: the pattern of early-universe fluctuations and how structures grow require a non-baryonic, invisible component.\\n- The Bullet Cluster: a collision of two clusters shows dark matter behaving differently from ordinary matter, reinforcing the idea of collisionless, invisible mass.\\n\\nWhat dark matter is (typical properties)\\n- Non-baryonic: not made of protons and neutrons in the ordinary sense.\\n- Weakly interacting (at least with light and regular matter): it does not shine, and it interacts only very weakly with normal matter except by gravity (and possibly very weakly by other forces in some models).\\n- Collisionless on large scales: it doesn\u2019t clump or heat up like normal gas in collisions.\\n- Most models call it \u201ccold\u201d dark matter: it moves slowly when it decouples from radiation in the early universe, helping form structure.\\n\\nCommon candidates (examples)\\n- WIMPs (weakly interacting massive particles): a leading theoretical class, heavier particles that interact via the weak force.\\n- Axions: very light particles motivated by solving a problem in particle physics; can act as dark matter.\\n- Sterile neutrinos: heavier cousins of neutrinos that interact even more weakly (only by gravity).\\n- MACHOs (baryonic compact objects like brown dwarfs): once considered, but they don\u2019t account for most of the dark matter given how much microlensing and other data constrain them.\\n- Other possibilities include \u201cfuzzy\u201d or ultra-light dark matter and self-interacting dark matter, which have distinct effects on structure.\\n\\nHow scientists look for dark matter\\n- Direct detection: underground detectors try to observe rare interactions between dark matter particles and atomic nuclei.\\n- Indirect detection: look for byproducts of dark matter annihilation or decay (gamma rays, neutrinos, cosmic rays) in space.\\n- Collider searches: produce dark matter particles in high-energy collisions (e.g., at the Large Hadron Collider) and look for missing energy signatures.\\n- Astrophysical and gravitational tests: study how dark matter would affect galaxies, clusters, lensing maps, and the CMB to constrain properties.\\n\\nCurrent status\\n- There is strong, converging evidence that dark matter exists and dominates the matter content of the universe (about a quarter to a fifth of the universe\u2019s energy density, with dark energy making up most of the rest; ordinary matter is only a few percent).\\n- No experimental detection of a dark matter particle has been universally confirmed yet. Experiments have placed tight limits on many popular candidates (especially WIMPs), while other candidates like axions are actively being hunted with dedicated experiments.\\n- The overall idea remains the simplest and most successful way to explain a wide range of observations, though scientists also explore alternative ideas (such as modifying gravity) that could explain some phenomena. So far, dark matter fits the data very well across many scales.\\n\\nWhy it matters\\n- Understanding dark matter is key to understanding how the universe formed and evolved.\\n- Identifying the particle or field behind dark matter would reveal new physics beyond the Standard Model.\\n- It connects cosmology (the universe as a whole) with particle physics (the fundamental constituents of matter).\\n\\nIn short\\nDark matter is the unseen stuff that gravity acts on on cosmic scales. It\u2019s not yet detected in the lab, but the gravitational fingerprints it leaves across galaxies, clusters, and the cosmos strongly support its existence. Scientists are actively searching for its particle nature and properties with multiple experimental avenues.\", \"generation_info\": {\"finish_reason\": \"stop\", \"logprobs\": null, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"protected_material_code\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"protected_material_text\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}, \"type\": \"ChatGeneration\", \"message\": {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"AIMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"Dark matter is a type of matter that does not emit, absorb, or reflect light, so we can\u2019t see it directly with telescopes. But we can see its gravity. Astrophysicists invoke dark matter to explain why galaxies rotate as they do, how galaxies cluster, and many features of the universe's large-scale structure.\\n\\nWhat we know (evidence in brief)\\n- Galaxy rotation curves: stars far from a galaxy\u2019s center orbit faster than visible matter alone would predict, implying extra unseen mass.\\n- Galaxy clusters: galaxies move as if they\u2019re wrapped in much more mass than the visible galaxies and hot gas indicate.\\n- Gravitational lensing: light from distant objects is bent by gravity in ways that reveal more mass than is visible.\\n- Cosmic microwave background (CMB) and structure formation: the pattern of early-universe fluctuations and how structures grow require a non-baryonic, invisible component.\\n- The Bullet Cluster: a collision of two clusters shows dark matter behaving differently from ordinary matter, reinforcing the idea of collisionless, invisible mass.\\n\\nWhat dark matter is (typical properties)\\n- Non-baryonic: not made of protons and neutrons in the ordinary sense.\\n- Weakly interacting (at least with light and regular matter): it does not shine, and it interacts only very weakly with normal matter except by gravity (and possibly very weakly by other forces in some models).\\n- Collisionless on large scales: it doesn\u2019t clump or heat up like normal gas in collisions.\\n- Most models call it \u201ccold\u201d dark matter: it moves slowly when it decouples from radiation in the early universe, helping form structure.\\n\\nCommon candidates (examples)\\n- WIMPs (weakly interacting massive particles): a leading theoretical class, heavier particles that interact via the weak force.\\n- Axions: very light particles motivated by solving a problem in particle physics; can act as dark matter.\\n- Sterile neutrinos: heavier cousins of neutrinos that interact even more weakly (only by gravity).\\n- MACHOs (baryonic compact objects like brown dwarfs): once considered, but they don\u2019t account for most of the dark matter given how much microlensing and other data constrain them.\\n- Other possibilities include \u201cfuzzy\u201d or ultra-light dark matter and self-interacting dark matter, which have distinct effects on structure.\\n\\nHow scientists look for dark matter\\n- Direct detection: underground detectors try to observe rare interactions between dark matter particles and atomic nuclei.\\n- Indirect detection: look for byproducts of dark matter annihilation or decay (gamma rays, neutrinos, cosmic rays) in space.\\n- Collider searches: produce dark matter particles in high-energy collisions (e.g., at the Large Hadron Collider) and look for missing energy signatures.\\n- Astrophysical and gravitational tests: study how dark matter would affect galaxies, clusters, lensing maps, and the CMB to constrain properties.\\n\\nCurrent status\\n- There is strong, converging evidence that dark matter exists and dominates the matter content of the universe (about a quarter to a fifth of the universe\u2019s energy density, with dark energy making up most of the rest; ordinary matter is only a few percent).\\n- No experimental detection of a dark matter particle has been universally confirmed yet. Experiments have placed tight limits on many popular candidates (especially WIMPs), while other candidates like axions are actively being hunted with dedicated experiments.\\n- The overall idea remains the simplest and most successful way to explain a wide range of observations, though scientists also explore alternative ideas (such as modifying gravity) that could explain some phenomena. So far, dark matter fits the data very well across many scales.\\n\\nWhy it matters\\n- Understanding dark matter is key to understanding how the universe formed and evolved.\\n- Identifying the particle or field behind dark matter would reveal new physics beyond the Standard Model.\\n- It connects cosmology (the universe as a whole) with particle physics (the fundamental constituents of matter).\\n\\nIn short\\nDark matter is the unseen stuff that gravity acts on on cosmic scales. It\u2019s not yet detected in the lab, but the gravitational fingerprints it leaves across galaxies, clusters, and the cosmos strongly support its existence. Scientists are actively searching for its particle nature and properties with multiple experimental avenues.\", \"additional_kwargs\": {\"refusal\": null}, \"response_metadata\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 2282, \"prompt_tokens\": 9, \"total_tokens\": 2291, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 1408, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 0}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-5-nano-2025-08-07\", \"system_fingerprint\": null, \"id\": \"chatcmpl-CtucnitHWFu6zp1debRRgqc2saLtQ\", \"prompt_filter_results\": [{\"prompt_index\": 0, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"jailbreak\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}], \"finish_reason\": \"stop\", \"logprobs\": null, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"protected_material_code\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"protected_material_text\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}, \"type\": \"ai\", \"id\": \"lc_run--019b83bd-080d-7011-9976-221a83422767-0\", \"usage_metadata\": {\"input_tokens\": 9, \"output_tokens\": 2282, \"total_tokens\": 2291, \"input_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"cache_read\": 0}, \"output_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"reasoning\": 1408}}, \"tool_calls\": [], \"invalid_tool_calls\": []}}}]], \"llm_output\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 2282, \"prompt_tokens\": 9, \"total_tokens\": 2291, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 1408, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 0}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-5-nano-2025-08-07\", \"system_fingerprint\": null, \"id\": \"chatcmpl-CtucnitHWFu6zp1debRRgqc2saLtQ\", \"prompt_filter_r