  "parent_id": null,
  "start_time": 1767441774911945984,
  "end_time": 1767441790299437056,
  "attributes": {
    "input.value": "{\"messages\": [[{\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"HumanMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"Explain Dark Matter\", \"type\": \"human\"}}]]}",
    "input.mime_type": "application/json",
    "output.value": "{\"generations\": [[{\"text\": \"Dark matter is a form of matter that does not emit, absorb, or reflect enough electromagnetic radiation for us to see it directly with telescopes. Yet it exerts gravity and clearly shapes the structure and evolution of the universe. Most scientists think it makes up a large part of the universe\u2019s matter content, but it is not the ordinary atoms that make up stars, planets, and us.\\n\\nKey ideas\\n\\n- What it is (in short)\\n  - Dark matter is invisible to light, but it gravitates.\\n  - It is non-baryonic (not made of the protons, neutrons, and electrons that make up ordinary matter) and interacts very weakly with normal matter and light.\\n  - It behaves differently from ordinary matter in the early universe, helping to seed and drive the formation of structures.\\n\\n- Why we\u2019re confident it exists (evidence)\\n  - Galaxy rotation curves: Stars far from a galaxy\u2019s center orbit too fast if only visible matter were present; extra mass inferred from gravity explains the speeds.\\n  - Gravitational lensing: Light from distant galaxies is bent by unseen mass; maps of this lensing show more mass than we can account for with stars and gas.\\n  - Cosmic microwave background (CMB): The pattern of temperature fluctuations and the way acoustic peaks appear in the CMB require a substantial amount of non-baryonic matter to fit the data.\\n  - Large-scale structure: The way galaxies cluster and the formation of the cosmic web fit well if there is a dark matter component that clumps under gravity early in the universe.\\n  - Bullet Cluster and similar systems: The gravitational mass (inferred from lensing) is offset from the ordinary matter, consistent with a separate, non-baryonic dark matter component.\\n\\n- How much and where\\n  - Dark matter accounts for roughly a quarter to a third of the universe\u2019s energy density and about 80\u201385% of all matter.\\n  - It forms halos around galaxies and clusters, acting as the \u201cscaffolding\u201d that helps ordinary matter collect and form stars and galaxies.\\n  - On large scales, dark matter is relatively smooth and cold (meaning its particles move slowly and cluster on small scales), which matches how structures grew over time.\\n\\n- What kind of particle or substance could it be?\\n  - WIMPs (Weakly Interacting Massive Particles): long-standing candidate; heavy particles that interact via gravity and the weak force.\\n  - Axions: very light particles originally proposed for other reasons; could be dark matter if they exist.\\n  - Sterile neutrinos: heavier, weakly interacting cousins of neutrinos.\\n  - Other ideas: self-interacting dark matter (DM particles that interact with each other more than with normal matter), fuzzy or ultra-light DM (very light bosons with wave-like behavior on galactic scales), and more.\\n  - MACHOs (Massive Compact Halo Objects) like black holes or faint stars were once considered, but searches show they cannot account for most of the dark matter.\\n\\n- How we try to detect it\\n  - Direct detection: extremely sensitive underground detectors look for rare collisions between dark matter particles and atomic nuclei, producing tiny recoils.\\n  - Indirect detection: search for byproducts of dark matter annihilation or decay (gamma rays, neutrinos, or cosmic rays) coming from regions of high dark matter density.\\n  - Collider production: high-energy accelerators (like the LHC) look for events with missing energy that could indicate dark matter particles produced in collisions escape the detector.\\n  - Astrophysical and cosmological measurements: increasingly precise CMB, galaxy surveys, gravitational lensing, and 21-cm observations constrain the properties of dark matter.\\n\\n- Why some people explore alternatives\\n  - Some theories modify gravity instead of adding unseen matter (for example, MOND and related ideas) to explain galaxy rotation curves. These can explain certain galaxy-scale observations but have trouble explaining clusters, the CMB, and large-scale structure as well as the dark matter framework does.\\n\\nWhat you should take away\\n\\n- Dark matter is a real, inferred component of the universe, inferred mainly from gravitational effects rather than direct light.\\n- It is very likely non-baryonic and interacts only very weakly with ordinary matter and light, though we\u2019re still trying to determine its exact nature.\\n- The leading picture\u2014cold dark matter\u2014fits a wide range of observations about galaxies and the cosmic structure while guiding ongoing experimental searches.\\n- We haven\u2019t yet detected a dark matter particle directly, but a broad program of experiments and observations is actively trying to measure its properties.\\n\\nIf you want, I can tailor this to a specific audience (kids, students, or a general adult audience), or dive into one aspect in more detail (for example, how galaxy rotation curves imply dark matter, or how direct detection experiments work).\", \"generation_info\": {\"finish_reason\": \"stop\", \"logprobs\": null, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"protected_material_code\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"protected_material_text\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}, \"type\": \"ChatGeneration\", \"message\": {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"AIMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"Dark matter is a form of matter that does not emit, absorb, or reflect enough electromagnetic radiation for us to see it directly with telescopes. Yet it exerts gravity and clearly shapes the structure and evolution of the universe. Most scientists think it makes up a large part of the universe\u2019s matter content, but it is not the ordinary atoms that make up stars, planets, and us.\\n\\nKey ideas\\n\\n- What it is (in short)\\n  - Dark matter is invisible to light, but it gravitates.\\n  - It is non-baryonic (not made of the protons, neutrons, and electrons that make up ordinary matter) and interacts very weakly with normal matter and light.\\n  - It behaves differently from ordinary matter in the early universe, helping to seed and drive the formation of structures.\\n\\n- Why we\u2019re confident it exists (evidence)\\n  - Galaxy rotation curves: Stars far from a galaxy\u2019s center orbit too fast if only visible matter were present; extra mass inferred from gravity explains the speeds.\\n  - Gravitational lensing: Light from distant galaxies is bent by unseen mass; maps of this lensing show more mass than we can account for with stars and gas.\\n  - Cosmic microwave background (CMB): The pattern of temperature fluctuations and the way acoustic peaks appear in the CMB require a substantial amount of non-baryonic matter to fit the data.\\n  - Large-scale structure: The way galaxies cluster and the formation of the cosmic web fit well if there is a dark matter component that clumps under gravity early in the universe.\\n  - Bullet Cluster and similar systems: The gravitational mass (inferred from lensing) is offset from the ordinary matter, consistent with a separate, non-baryonic dark matter component.\\n\\n- How much and where\\n  - Dark matter accounts for roughly a quarter to a third of the universe\u2019s energy density and about 80\u201385% of all matter.\\n  - It forms halos around galaxies and clusters, acting as the \u201cscaffolding\u201d that helps ordinary matter collect and form stars and galaxies.\\n  - On large scales, dark matter is relatively smooth and cold (meaning its particles move slowly and cluster on small scales), which matches how structures grew over time.\\n\\n- What kind of particle or substance could it be?\\n  - WIMPs (Weakly Interacting Massive Particles): long-standing candidate; heavy particles that interact via gravity and the weak force.\\n  - Axions: very light particles originally proposed for other reasons; could be dark matter if they exist.\\n  - Sterile neutrinos: heavier, weakly interacting cousins of neutrinos.\\n  - Other ideas: self-interacting dark matter (DM particles that interact with each other more than with normal matter), fuzzy or ultra-light DM (very light bosons with wave-like behavior on galactic scales), and more.\\n  - MACHOs (Massive Compact Halo Objects) like black holes or faint stars were once considered, but searches show they cannot account for most of the dark matter.\\n\\n- How we try to detect it\\n  - Direct detection: extremely sensitive underground detectors look for rare collisions between dark matter particles and atomic nuclei, producing tiny recoils.\\n  - Indirect detection: search for byproducts of dark matter annihilation or decay (gamma rays, neutrinos, or cosmic rays) coming from regions of high dark matter density.\\n  - Collider production: high-energy accelerators (like the LHC) look for events with missing energy that could indicate dark matter particles produced in collisions escape the detector.\\n  - Astrophysical and cosmological measurements: increasingly precise CMB, galaxy surveys, gravitational lensing, and 21-cm observations constrain the properties of dark matter.\\n\\n- Why some people explore alternatives\\n  - Some theories modify gravity instead of adding unseen matter (for example, MOND and related ideas) to explain galaxy rotation curves. These can explain certain galaxy-scale observations but have trouble explaining clusters, the CMB, and large-scale structure as well as the dark matter framework does.\\n\\nWhat you should take away\\n\\n- Dark matter is a real, inferred component of the universe, inferred mainly from gravitational effects rather than direct light.\\n- It is very likely non-baryonic and interacts only very weakly with ordinary matter and light, though we\u2019re still trying to determine its exact nature.\\n- The leading picture\u2014cold dark matter\u2014fits a wide range of observations about galaxies and the cosmic structure while guiding ongoing experimental searches.\\n- We haven\u2019t yet detected a dark matter particle directly, but a broad program of experiments and observations is actively trying to measure its properties.\\n\\nIf you want, I can tailor this to a specific audience (kids, students, or a general adult audience), or dive into one aspect in more detail (for example, how galaxy rotation curves imply dark matter, or how direct detection experiments work).\", \"additional_kwargs\": {\"refusal\": null}, \"response_metadata\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 2144, \"prompt_tokens\": 9, \"total_tokens\": 2153, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 1152, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 0}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-5-nano-2025-08-07\", \"system_fingerprint\": null, \"id\": \"chatcmpl-CtucztQq60I6FnxcmXyV8fy3ZglAz\", \"prompt_filter_results\": [{\"prompt_index\": 0, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"jailbreak\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}], \"finish_reason\": \"stop\", \"logprobs\": null, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"protected_material_code\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"protected_material_text\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}, \"type\": \"ai\", \"id\": \"lc_run--019b83bd-393f-7fb2-aec1-c79e8e302f0d-0\", \"usage_metadata\": {\"input_tokens\": 9, \"output_tokens\": 2144, \"total_tokens\": 2153, \"input_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"cache_read\": 0}, \"output_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"reasoning\": 1152}}, \"tool_calls\": [], \"invalid_tool_calls\": []}}}]], \"llm_output\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 2144, \"prompt_tokens\": 9, \"total_tokens\": 2153, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 1152, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 0}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-5-nano-2025-08-07\", \"system_fingerprint\": null, \"id\": \"chatcmpl-CtucztQq60I6FnxcmXyV8fy3ZglAz\", \"prompt_filter_results\": [{\"prompt_index\": 0, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"jailbreak\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}]}, \"run\": null, \"type\": \"LLMResult\"}",
    "output.mime_type": "application/json",
    "llm.input_messages.0.message.role": "user",
    "llm.input_messages.0.message.content": "Explain Dark Matter",
    "llm.output_messages.0.message.role": "assistant",
    "llm.output_messages.0.message.content": "Dark matter is a form of matter that does not emit, absorb, or reflect enough electromagnetic radiation for us to see it directly with telescopes. Yet it exerts gravity and clearly shapes the structure and evolution of the universe. Most scientists think it makes up a large part of the universe\u2019s matter content, but it is not the ordinary atoms that make up stars, planets, and us.\n\nKey ideas\n\n- What it is (in short)\n  - Dark matter is invisible to light, but it gravitates.\n  - It is non-baryonic (not made of the protons, neutrons, and electrons that make up ordinary matter) and interacts very weakly with normal matter and light.\n  - It behaves differently from ordinary matter in the early universe, helping to seed and drive the formation of structures.\n\n- Why we\u2019re confident it exists (evidence)\n  - Galaxy rotation curves: Stars far from a galaxy\u2019s center orbit too fast if only visible matter were present; extra mass inferred from gravity explains the speeds.\n  - Gravitational lensing: Light from distant galaxies is bent by unseen mass; maps of this lensing show more mass than we can account for with stars and gas.\n  - Cosmic microwave background (CMB): The pattern of temperature fluctuations and the way acoustic peaks appear in the CMB require a substantial amount of non-baryonic matter to fit the data.\n  - Large-scale structure: The way galaxies cluster and the formation of the cosmic web fit well if there is a dark matter component that clumps under gravity early in the universe.\n  - Bullet Cluster and similar systems: The gravitational mass (inferred from lensing) is offset from the ordinary matter, consistent with a separate, non-baryonic dark matter component.\n\n- How much and where\n  - Dark matter accounts for roughly a quarter to a third of the universe\u2019s energy density and about 80\u201385% of all matter.\n  - It forms halos around galaxies and clusters, acting as the \u201cscaffolding\u201d that helps ordinary matter collect and form stars and galaxies.\n  - On large scales, dark matter is relatively smooth and cold (meaning its particles move slowly and cluster on small scales), which matches how structures grew over time.\n\n- What kind of particle or substance could it be?\n  - WIMPs (Weakly Interacting Massive Particles): long-standing candidate; heavy particles that interact via gravity and the weak force.\n  - Axions: very light particles originally proposed for other reasons; could be dark matter if they exist.\n  - Sterile neutrinos: heavier, weakly interacting cousins of neutrinos.\n  - Other ideas: self-interacting dark matter (DM particles that interact with each other more than with normal matter), fuzzy or ultra-light DM (very light bosons with wave-like behavior on galactic scales), and more.\n  - MACHOs (Massive Compact Halo Objects) like black holes or faint stars were once considered, but searches show they cannot account for most of the dark matter.\n\n- How we try to detect it\n  - Direct detection: extremely sensitive underground detectors look for rare collisions between dark matter particles and atomic nuclei, producing tiny recoils.\n  - Indirect detection: search for byproducts of dark matter annihilation or decay (gamma rays, neutrinos, or cosmic rays) coming from regions of high dark matter density.\n  - Collider production: high-energy accelerators (like the LHC) look for events with missing energy that could indicate dark matter particles produced in collisions escape the detector.\n  - Astrophysical and cosmological measurements: increasingly precise CMB, galaxy surveys, gravitational lensing, and 21-cm observations constrain the properties of dark matter.\n\n- Why some people explore alternatives\n  - Some theories modify gravity instead of adding unseen matter (for example, MOND and related ideas) to explain galaxy rotation curves. These can explain certain galaxy-scale observations but have trouble explaining clusters, the CMB, and large-scale structure as well as the dark matter framework does.\n\nWhat you should take away\n\n- Dark matter is a real, inferred component of the universe, inferred mainly from gravitational effects rather than direct light.\n- It is very likely non-baryonic and interacts only very weakly with ordinary matter and light, though we\u2019re still trying to determine its exact nature.\n- The leading picture\u2014cold dark matter\u2014fits a wide range of observations about galaxies and the cosmic structure while guiding ongoing experimental searches.\n- We haven\u2019t yet detected a dark matter particle directly, but a broad program of experiments and observations is actively trying to measure its properties.\n\nIf you want, I can tailor this to a specific audience (kids, students, or a general adult audience), or dive into one aspect in more detail (for example, how galaxy rotation curves imply dark matter, or how direct detection experiments work).",
    "llm.invocation_parameters": "{\"model\": null, \"azure_deployment\": \"gpt-5-nano\", \"model_name\": null, \"stream\": false, \"_type\": \"azure-openai-chat\", \"stop\": null}",
