  "parent_id": null,
  "start_time": 1767441803008932096,
  "end_time": 1767441822558119168,
  "attributes": {
    "input.value": "{\"messages\": [[{\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"SystemMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"You are a helpful assistant for Neatlogs\", \"type\": \"system\"}}, {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"HumanMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"Explain V3 Architecture\", \"type\": \"human\"}}]]}",
    "input.mime_type": "application/json",
    "output.value": "{\"generations\": [[{\"text\": \"There isn\u2019t a single universal standard called \u201cV3 Architecture.\u201d Different teams use \u201cV3\u201d to mean different things. In many modern software and log-analytics platforms, a practical interpretation of V3 is a three-layer (three-stage) architecture that focuses on Ingest \u2192 Process/Enrich \u2192 Store+Query+Visualize. Below is a clear, Neatlogs-relevant explanation you can use as a starting point. If you have a specific Neatlogs doc or context, share it and I\u2019ll tailor precisely.\\n\\nWhat \u201cV3 Architecture\u201d often means\\n- V = a phase or layer, and 3 = three core stages in a data flow for logs and events.\\n- Common mapping: Ingest (edge/shippers) \u2192 Processing/Enrichment (validation, normalization, routing) \u2192 Storage and Visualization (search, analytics, dashboards).\\n\\nThree layers and what they do\\n1) Ingest Layer (Edge/Collector)\\n- Purpose: reliably collect logs from all sources and normalize at the edge.\\n- Components:\\n  - Log shippers/agents (e.g., lightweight collectors on hosts, container sidecars, or agentless collectors).\\n  - Ingest APIs/gateways to receive data from multiple producers.\\n  - Basic pre-processing: batching, compression, basic filtering, humility checks, add metadata (host, app, environment, tags).\\n- Key considerations:\\n  - Backpressure resilience, retries, idempotency.\\n  - Security at the edge (encryption in transit, auth for sources).\\n  - Lightweight and scalable to handle bursts.\\n\\n2) Processing/Enrichment Layer\\n- Purpose: ensure logs are usable for searching and analytics by validating, parsing, enriching, and routing them.\\n- Components:\\n  - Parsers/ Normalizers: convert diverse log formats into a structured schema (JSON, structured fields).\\n  - Validation: schema checks, data quality rules, deduplication.\\n  - Enrichment: attach richer metadata (geo, user/context, service lineage, correlation IDs).\\n  - Routing/Orchestration: decide which stores or indices receive which data (multi-tenant routing, retention-aware routing).\\n- Key considerations:\\n  - Schema registry and versioning to handle evolving log formats.\\n  - Idempotent processing to ensure exactly-once or at-least-once semantics as needed.\\n  - Observability: track processing latency, failure rates, and reprocessing needs.\\n\\n3) Storage/Query/Visualization Layer\\n- Purpose: store logs securely, enable fast search/analytics, and present results to users.\\n- Sub-layers:\\n  - Raw/Long-term Storage: keep original logs (e.g., object storage) for compliance and rehydration.\\n  - Index/Search Layer: structured indices for fast queries (e.g., a search engine or time-series index) with derived metrics.\\n  - Query API: programmatic access for dashboards, alerts, and integrations.\\n  - Visualization/UX: dashboards, ad-hoc queries, alerting rules, and admin interfaces.\\n- Key considerations:\\n  - Retention policies, lifecycle management, and cost controls.\\n  - Multi-region replication, high availability, and disaster recovery.\\n  - Security and access control (RBAC, data isolation per tenant/project).\\n  - Observability: metrics and traces around query latency, index health, and storage usage.\\n\\nHow data typically flows in V3\\n- Producers (apps, services, hosts) emit logs.\\n- Ingest Layer receives and streams logs to the Processing Layer.\\n- Processing Layer parses, validates, and enriches logs, then routes them to Storage/Query layers.\\n- Users or automated systems query the data via the UI or API, and dashboards/alerts present insights.\\n\\nNon-functional considerations you\u2019ll likely want in a V3 setup\\n- Reliability: backpressure handling, replayable pipelines, idempotent processing.\\n- Scalability: horizontal scaling of ingest, processing, and storage layers; autoscaling where possible.\\n- Observability: end-to-end tracing, metrics for ingestion rate, processing latency, and query performance.\\n- Security/compliance: encryption in transit, access controls, audit logs, retention governance.\\n- Migration/versioning: clean path from V2 to V3 with backward-compatibility and feature flags.\\n\\nHow this maps to Neatlogs (a practical blueprint)\\n- Ingest: agents and collectors on all apps/hosts push logs to a secure Ingest API. Add metadata like source, environment, and service.\\n- Processing: a centralized pipeline validates/normalizes logs, parses structured fields, enriches with context (trace IDs, user IDs), and routes data to the right storage or indices.\\n- Storage/Query/Visualization: raw logs are archived for compliance; structured/logged data is indexed for fast search; a UI presents dashboards, alerts, and investigations. Admin tools enforce retention, permissions, and data governance.\\n\\nIf you\u2019re upgrading or defining a V3 for Neatlogs specifically\\n- Start with a clear boundary between layers and define API contracts between them.\\n- Version your schemas and support backward compatibility.\\n- Plan for multi-tenant separation, roles, and access controls across the UI and APIs.\\n- Build observability into each layer (health checks, metrics, logs about the pipeline itself).\\n- Create migration paths from V2 to V3 with feature flags and staged rollouts.\\n\\nNext steps\\n- Tell me which \u201cV3 Architecture\u201d you mean (Neatlogs internal doc, a specific product pattern, or a general three-layer pattern).\\n- If you can share current architecture diagrams or goals (latency targets, data volumes, retention needs, security requirements), I can tailor a concrete V3 blueprint, including component choices, data schema, and deployment notes.\", \"generation_info\": {\"finish_reason\": \"stop\", \"logprobs\": null, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"protected_material_code\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"protected_material_text\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}, \"type\": \"ChatGeneration\", \"message\": {\"lc\": 1, \"type\": \"constructor\", \"id\": [\"langchain\", \"schema\", \"messages\", \"AIMessage\"], \"kwargs\": {\"content\": \"There isn\u2019t a single universal standard called \u201cV3 Architecture.\u201d Different teams use \u201cV3\u201d to mean different things. In many modern software and log-analytics platforms, a practical interpretation of V3 is a three-layer (three-stage) architecture that focuses on Ingest \u2192 Process/Enrich \u2192 Store+Query+Visualize. Below is a clear, Neatlogs-relevant explanation you can use as a starting point. If you have a specific Neatlogs doc or context, share it and I\u2019ll tailor precisely.\\n\\nWhat \u201cV3 Architecture\u201d often means\\n- V = a phase or layer, and 3 = three core stages in a data flow for logs and events.\\n- Common mapping: Ingest (edge/shippers) \u2192 Processing/Enrichment (validation, normalization, routing) \u2192 Storage and Visualization (search, analytics, dashboards).\\n\\nThree layers and what they do\\n1) Ingest Layer (Edge/Collector)\\n- Purpose: reliably collect logs from all sources and normalize at the edge.\\n- Components:\\n  - Log shippers/agents (e.g., lightweight collectors on hosts, container sidecars, or agentless collectors).\\n  - Ingest APIs/gateways to receive data from multiple producers.\\n  - Basic pre-processing: batching, compression, basic filtering, humility checks, add metadata (host, app, environment, tags).\\n- Key considerations:\\n  - Backpressure resilience, retries, idempotency.\\n  - Security at the edge (encryption in transit, auth for sources).\\n  - Lightweight and scalable to handle bursts.\\n\\n2) Processing/Enrichment Layer\\n- Purpose: ensure logs are usable for searching and analytics by validating, parsing, enriching, and routing them.\\n- Components:\\n  - Parsers/ Normalizers: convert diverse log formats into a structured schema (JSON, structured fields).\\n  - Validation: schema checks, data quality rules, deduplication.\\n  - Enrichment: attach richer metadata (geo, user/context, service lineage, correlation IDs).\\n  - Routing/Orchestration: decide which stores or indices receive which data (multi-tenant routing, retention-aware routing).\\n- Key considerations:\\n  - Schema registry and versioning to handle evolving log formats.\\n  - Idempotent processing to ensure exactly-once or at-least-once semantics as needed.\\n  - Observability: track processing latency, failure rates, and reprocessing needs.\\n\\n3) Storage/Query/Visualization Layer\\n- Purpose: store logs securely, enable fast search/analytics, and present results to users.\\n- Sub-layers:\\n  - Raw/Long-term Storage: keep original logs (e.g., object storage) for compliance and rehydration.\\n  - Index/Search Layer: structured indices for fast queries (e.g., a search engine or time-series index) with derived metrics.\\n  - Query API: programmatic access for dashboards, alerts, and integrations.\\n  - Visualization/UX: dashboards, ad-hoc queries, alerting rules, and admin interfaces.\\n- Key considerations:\\n  - Retention policies, lifecycle management, and cost controls.\\n  - Multi-region replication, high availability, and disaster recovery.\\n  - Security and access control (RBAC, data isolation per tenant/project).\\n  - Observability: metrics and traces around query latency, index health, and storage usage.\\n\\nHow data typically flows in V3\\n- Producers (apps, services, hosts) emit logs.\\n- Ingest Layer receives and streams logs to the Processing Layer.\\n- Processing Layer parses, validates, and enriches logs, then routes them to Storage/Query layers.\\n- Users or automated systems query the data via the UI or API, and dashboards/alerts present insights.\\n\\nNon-functional considerations you\u2019ll likely want in a V3 setup\\n- Reliability: backpressure handling, replayable pipelines, idempotent processing.\\n- Scalability: horizontal scaling of ingest, processing, and storage layers; autoscaling where possible.\\n- Observability: end-to-end tracing, metrics for ingestion rate, processing latency, and query performance.\\n- Security/compliance: encryption in transit, access controls, audit logs, retention governance.\\n- Migration/versioning: clean path from V2 to V3 with backward-compatibility and feature flags.\\n\\nHow this maps to Neatlogs (a practical blueprint)\\n- Ingest: agents and collectors on all apps/hosts push logs to a secure Ingest API. Add metadata like source, environment, and service.\\n- Processing: a centralized pipeline validates/normalizes logs, parses structured fields, enriches with context (trace IDs, user IDs), and routes data to the right storage or indices.\\n- Storage/Query/Visualization: raw logs are archived for compliance; structured/logged data is indexed for fast search; a UI presents dashboards, alerts, and investigations. Admin tools enforce retention, permissions, and data governance.\\n\\nIf you\u2019re upgrading or defining a V3 for Neatlogs specifically\\n- Start with a clear boundary between layers and define API contracts between them.\\n- Version your schemas and support backward compatibility.\\n- Plan for multi-tenant separation, roles, and access controls across the UI and APIs.\\n- Build observability into each layer (health checks, metrics, logs about the pipeline itself).\\n- Create migration paths from V2 to V3 with feature flags and staged rollouts.\\n\\nNext steps\\n- Tell me which \u201cV3 Architecture\u201d you mean (Neatlogs internal doc, a specific product pattern, or a general three-layer pattern).\\n- If you can share current architecture diagrams or goals (latency targets, data volumes, retention needs, security requirements), I can tailor a concrete V3 blueprint, including component choices, data schema, and deployment notes.\", \"additional_kwargs\": {\"refusal\": null}, \"response_metadata\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 3665, \"prompt_tokens\": 23, \"total_tokens\": 3688, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 2496, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 0}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-5-nano-2025-08-07\", \"system_fingerprint\": null, \"id\": \"chatcmpl-CtudRR7fAswpdAryJbfK16iwXOwLy\", \"prompt_filter_results\": [{\"prompt_index\": 0, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"jailbreak\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}], \"finish_reason\": \"stop\", \"logprobs\": null, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"protected_material_code\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"protected_material_text\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}, \"type\": \"ai\", \"id\": \"lc_run--019b83bd-a701-77d2-ace7-fa6f9b2ce41c-0\", \"usage_metadata\": {\"input_tokens\": 23, \"output_tokens\": 3665, \"total_tokens\": 3688, \"input_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"cache_read\": 0}, \"output_token_details\": {\"audio\": 0, \"reasoning\": 2496}}, \"tool_calls\": [], \"invalid_tool_calls\": []}}}]], \"llm_output\": {\"token_usage\": {\"completion_tokens\": 3665, \"prompt_tokens\": 23, \"total_tokens\": 3688, \"completion_tokens_details\": {\"accepted_prediction_tokens\": 0, \"audio_tokens\": 0, \"reasoning_tokens\": 2496, \"rejected_prediction_tokens\": 0}, \"prompt_tokens_details\": {\"audio_tokens\": 0, \"cached_tokens\": 0}}, \"model_provider\": \"openai\", \"model_name\": \"gpt-5-nano-2025-08-07\", \"system_fingerprint\": null, \"id\": \"chatcmpl-CtudRR7fAswpdAryJbfK16iwXOwLy\", \"prompt_filter_results\": [{\"prompt_index\": 0, \"content_filter_results\": {\"hate\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"jailbreak\": {\"filtered\": false, \"detected\": false}, \"self_harm\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"sexual\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}, \"violence\": {\"filtered\": false, \"severity\": \"safe\"}}}]}, \"run\": null, \"type\": \"LLMResult\"}",
